#include <cmath>

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());

        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference between medians.
        // Let the sorted array be a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // Consider the case where one class has size 1 and the other has size 2n-1.
        // If class 1 has size 1, its median is its single element.
        // If class 2 has size 2n-1, its median is the element at index (2n-1-1)/2 = n-1 (0-indexed)
        // among its own elements.
        //
        // It can be proven that the optimal strategy is to pick the smallest n elements
        // for one class and the largest n elements for the other class,
        // or more generally, to split the sorted array into two halves.
        //
        // Specifically, if we sort the entire array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1},
        // and we want to form two classes of odd sizes S1 and S2 such that S1+S2 = 2n.
        //
        // The median of a class of size 2k+1 is its (k+1)-th smallest element.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_{n-1} and a_n from the sorted array.
        //
        // If we form one class using elements a_0, ..., a_{n-1} and another using a_n, ..., a_{2n-1},
        // this is not necessarily valid because class sizes must be odd.
        //
        // However, if we consider the elements a_{n-1} and a_n,
        // a_{n-1} is the largest element in the first half of the sorted array (indices 0 to n-1).
        // a_n is the smallest element in the second half of the sorted array (indices n to 2n-1).
        //
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // the medians themselves should be as close as possible.
        //
        // If we pick a_i as the median for one class and a_j as the median for another,
        // we need to ensure that we can form valid classes around these medians.
        //
        // For any partition into two odd-sized classes, say of sizes $S_1$ and $S_2$,
        // the median of the first class will be some $a_i$ and the median of the second class will be some $a_j$.
        //
        // It turns out that the minimum difference is always achieved by taking
        // the element at index $n-1$ and the element at index $n$ from the globally sorted array.
        //
        // Let's verify this.
        // Suppose we have $2n$ students.
        // The median of a class of size $2k+1$ is the $(k+1)$-th element.
        //
        // Consider the two elements $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ from the sorted array.
        //
        // We can form a class $C_1$ of size $2n-1$ using all students except $a_{n-1}$.
        // The median of $C_1$ would be $a_n$ (if $a_{n-1}$ is removed, $a_n$ becomes the $(n-1)$-th element).
        // This is not quite right.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than it looks.
        // The minimum possible difference between the medians of two classes, each of odd size,
        // is simply the difference between the $n$-th smallest element and the $(n+1)$-th smallest element
        // in the overall sorted list of $2n$ students.
        //
        // This is because we can always construct two classes such that $a_{n-1}$ is the median of one class
        // and $a_n$ is the median of the other.
        //
        // For example, let $C_1 = \{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$ and $C_2 = \{a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // This is not a valid partition because $C_1$ and $C_2$ both have size $n$, which might be even.
        //
        // However, we can always make $a_{n-1}$ the median of one class and $a_n$ the median of another.
        //
        // Consider the partition where:
        // Class 1: $\{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$ (size $n$)
        // Class 2: $\{a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$ (size $n$)
        // This is not valid if $n$ is even.
        //
        // The problem statement implies that we can choose any odd sizes $S_1, S_2$ such that $S_1+S_2=2n$.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort all $2n$ skill levels, $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$,
        // the median of any class of size $2k+1$ will be some $a_i$.
        //
        // If we want to minimize $|M_1 - M_2|$, where $M_1$ and $M_2$ are medians,
        // we should pick $M_1$ and $M_2$ to be adjacent elements in the sorted list $a$.
        //
        // Can we always make $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ the medians of two valid classes?
        // Yes.
        // Let $M_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 = a_n$.
        //
        // Class 1: $\{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$ (size $2n-1$)
        // Class 2: $\{a_n\}$ (size 1)
        //
        // In this case, the median of Class 2 is $a_n$.
        // The median of Class 1 (size $2n-1$) is the $(n)$-th element.
        // If we remove $a_n$ from the full sorted list, the elements are
        // $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // The $(n)$-th element (0-indexed) in this list is $a_{n-1}$.
        // So, the medians are $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        // The difference is $|a_n - a_{n-1}|$.
        //
        // This construction always works and gives a difference of $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // Can we do better? No, because any two medians $M_1, M_2$ must be some $a_i, a_j$.
        // The minimum possible difference between any two elements $a_i, a_j$ from the sorted array
        // is $a_k - a_{k-1}$ for some $k$.
        //
        // The specific choice of $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ is optimal because it represents the "middle split"
        // of the entire dataset. Any other split would involve medians further apart.
        //
        // The problem is essentially asking for the minimum difference between two elements $a_i$ and $a_j$
        // such that $a_i$ can be the median of an odd-sized class and $a_j$ can be the median of another odd-sized class,
        // and these two classes form a partition of all students.
        //
        // The minimum difference between any two elements in a sorted array is between adjacent elements.
        // The specific adjacent elements $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ are chosen because they are the "middle" elements.
        //
        // The answer is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.

        std::cout << a[n] - a[n - 1] << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

